To build a user dashboard that displays recent orders with a search bar and filters, we can use a combination of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the front-end, along with a back-end framework (like Node.js with Express) to handle data fetching. Below is a step-by-step guide to create a simple version of this dashboard.

### Step 1: Set Up the Project Structure

Create a project directory with the following structure:

```
/user-dashboard
  ├── /public
  │   ├── index.html
  │   ├── styles.css
  │   └── script.js
  ├── /server
  │   └── server.js
  └── package.json
```

### Step 2: Initialize the Project

Navigate to the project directory and initialize a Node.js project:

```bash
cd user-dashboard
npm init -y
```

### Step 3: Install Required Packages

Install Express for the server:

```bash
npm install express
```

### Step 4: Create the Server

In `server/server.js`, set up a basic Express server that serves the static files and provides an endpoint for recent orders.

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

// Sample data for recent orders
const orders = [
    { id: 1, product: 'Laptop', date: '2023-10-01', status: 'Shipped' },
    { id: 2, product: 'Phone', date: '2023-10-02', status: 'Pending' },
    { id: 3, product: 'Tablet', date: '2023-10-03', status: 'Delivered' },
    // Add more sample orders as needed
];

// Middleware to serve static files
app.use(express.static('public'));

// Endpoint to get recent orders
app.get('/api/orders', (req, res) => {
    res.json(orders);
});

// Start the server
app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

### Step 5: Create the HTML Structure

In `public/index.html`, create the basic structure for the dashboard.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <title>User Dashboard</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Recent Orders</h1>
        <input type="text" id="searchBar" placeholder="Search orders...">
        <select id="statusFilter">
            <option value="">All Statuses</option>
            <option value="Shipped">Shipped</option>
            <option value="Pending">Pending</option>
            <option value="Delivered">Delivered</option>
        </select>
        <table id="ordersTable">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>ID</th>
                    <th>Product</th>
                    <th>Date</th>
                    <th>Status</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <!-- Orders will be populated here -->
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Step 6: Style the Dashboard

In `public/styles.css`, add some basic styles.

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 20px;
}

.container {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: auto;
}

input, select {
    margin: 10px 0;
    padding: 10px;
    width: 100%;
}

table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
}

th, td {
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 8px;
}

th {
    background-color: #f2f2f2;
}
```

### Step 7: Add JavaScript for Functionality

In `public/script.js`, add the functionality to fetch orders and implement search and filter.

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const searchBar = document.getElementById('searchBar');
    const statusFilter = document.getElementById('statusFilter');
    const ordersTableBody = document.querySelector('#ordersTable tbody');

    // Function to fetch orders from the server
    const fetchOrders = async () => {
        const response = await fetch('/api/orders');
        const orders = await response.json();
        displayOrders(orders);
    };

    // Function to display orders in the table
    const displayOrders = (orders) => {
        ordersTableBody.innerHTML = '';
        orders.forEach(order => {
            const row = document.createElement('tr');
            row.innerHTML = `
                <td>${order.id}</td>
                <td>${order.product}</td>
                <td>${order.date}</td>
                <td>${order.status}</td>
            `;
            ordersTableBody.appendChild(row);
        });
    };

    // Function to filter orders
    const filterOrders = () => {
        const searchTerm = searchBar.value.toLowerCase();
        const selectedStatus = statusFilter.value;

        fetch('/api/orders')
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(orders => {
                const filteredOrders = orders.filter(order => {
                    const matchesSearch = order.product.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm);
                    const matchesStatus = selectedStatus ? order.status === selectedStatus : true;
                    return matchesSearch && matchesStatus;
                });
                displayOrders(filteredOrders);
            });
    };

    // Event listeners for search and filter
    searchBar.addEventListener('input', filterOrders);
    statusFilter.addEventListener('change', filterOrders);

    // Initial fetch of orders
    fetchOrders();
});
```

### Step 8: Run the Application

1. Start the server:

```bash
node server/server.js
```

2. Open your browser and navigate to `http://localhost:3000`.

### Conclusion

You now have a simple user dashboard that displays recent orders with a search bar and filters. You can expand this project by adding more features, such as pagination, sorting, or connecting to a real database.
